    "en": {
      "100h1":"Functional Ear Training",
      "200h2":"The Skill You’ll Learn And The Approach You’ll Use",
      "300p":"When you first picked up your instrument I’m sure you wanted to jump right in and start playing your favourite tunes. Then you discovered that it’s impossible to play those tunes until you’ve learned the notes and developed a little bit of technique.",
      "400p":" Ear training is just the same. You might want to jump straight into it so you can begin the wonderful transformation that awaits you (and I want you to as well!) but there are a couple of things you need to understand first, so getting started is nice and easy (and not frustrating!). Fortunately, it will only take a few minutes to learn everything you need to so you can dive in and we’ll cover it all in this short introduction. ",
      "500p":" You’re about to learn about the specific skill you’ll develop in this course (called relative pitch) and the approach you’ll use to develop it (called tonality based ear training). Even if you’re an old hand when it comes to ear training I recommend you give it a quick read as you’ll learn why using a tonality based approach to develop relative pitch is absolutely essential if you want to experience great results with ear training. ",
      "600h3":"What is relative pitch?",
      "700p":" For those new to ear training relative pitch can appear a little counterintuitive. ",
      "800p":" With relative pitch you won’t learn to recognise the notes in music themselves. Instead you’ll learn to recognise the relationships between them (relative pitch - relationships, makes sense right?). ",
      "900p":" If you were to hear a single note played, you wouldn’t be able to recognise it with relative pitch. But if a second note is then played you would know what it is in relation to the first note. This means that if you know what any one note is you can recognise any other note (or group of notes) easily, simply using the first note as a reference point. ",
      "1000h3":"Why do we focus on relative pitch?",
      "1100p":"Relative pitch isn’t the only way that musicians can recognise and play music by ear.",
      "1200p":"The other approach is called perfect (or absolute) pitch.",
      "1300p":" With perfect pitch a musician recognises each note itself. So if a single note is played, you could recognise it straightaway if you had perfect pitch. You wouldn’t need a reference point. ",
      "1400p":"This sounds ideal but there’s a problem: you’re not going to develop it.",
      "1500p":" Perfect pitch is a hotly debated topic among musicians and I don’t want to weigh in here, (because I want to get past the debating and into the ear training) but there’s a lot of evidence that supports the idea that perfect pitch can only be developed in childhood. ",
      "1600p":" As a result, if you don’t have it already you’re better off forgetting about perfect pitch (read more about relative pitch vs perfect pitch) ",
      "1700p":" The good (great even!) news is that relative pitch can be developed by anyone at any age, and when approached in the right way it can be done quickly and painlessly, and the benefits are the same (and some would say even greater) than they are with perfect pitch. ",
      "1800p":" So how does one approach it in the right way? ",
      "1900p":" With a tonality based approach. ",
      "2000h3":"What is a tonality based approach to ear training?",
      "2100p":"A tonality based approach to ear training is built around a single note, called the tonic.",
      "2200p":" The tonic is the central note in a piece of music. It sounds the most stable and at rest and it’s the note that every other note resolves back to. Just about every piece of music ends on the tonic. ",
      "2300h3":"Why do we use a tonality based approach?",
      "2400p":" The reason a tonality based approach to ear training is so effective is because the tonic is the easiest note to learn to recognise and it’s very stable. This makes it the perfect note to use as our reference point (which we need if we want to play music by ear with relative pitch). ",
      "2500p":" This approach is very different from the other common approach to ear training, called an interval based approach. An interval based approach focuses on the difference in pitch between each individual note (called an interval). While it makes sense to focus on these intervals it’s useless in practice. You’ll learn to recognise the intervals in the exercises but it won’t help at all when you’re listening to or playing real music because you have no stable reference point to rely on (read more about tonal ear training vs interval ear training) ",
      "2600h3":"Summary",
